% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Death Penalty
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro74).  % [pro] If people weigh the arguments properly and have empathy for the victims, people will be more inclined to favor capital punishment.
arg(pro5).  % [pro] According to a study conducted in the late 1960s, there was a 7% crime rate increase in the years when the death penalty law was abolished.
arg(pro55).  % [pro] Capital punishment is not excessive for people who knowingly and intentionally commit premeditated murder.
arg(pro55b).  % [pro] Capital punishment is not an unnecessary punishment for people who knowingly and intentionally commit premeditated murder.
arg(pro62).  % [pro] It is fair that people who violate other people's lives are brought to justice.
arg(pro62b).  % [pro] It is fair that people who violate other people's lives suffer the fate they rightfully deserve.
arg(pro2).  % [pro] Call your state legislature representatives today to enforce the death penalty in your state!
arg(pro27).  % [pro] The possibility that an execution method may cause pain, whether by accident or as an unavoidable consequence of death, does not meet the standard of an "objectively intolerable risk of harm" required to be considered cruel and unusual.
arg(pro27b).  % [pro] Kentucky has adopted an execution method that is regarded as the most humane currently available and is also used by thirty‑five other states.
arg(pro27c).  % [pro] Kentucky's decision to continue using its execution protocol cannot be taken as evidence of wanton infliction of pain prohibited by the Eighth Amendment.
arg(pro27d).  % [pro] In U.S. legal history, whenever a method of execution has been challenged before the Supreme Court as cruel and unusual, the Court has consistently rejected the challenge.
arg(pro60).  % [pro] Life is sacred.
arg(pro60b).  % [pro] A person who takes a life should have the taker's own life taken away as well.
arg(con211).  % [con] The legal system does not provide adequate representation to the poor in cases where a life hangs in the balance, so it does not provide equal justice under the law.
arg(con72).  % [con] The notion of an eye for an eye, or a life for a life, is a simplistic one.
arg(con208).  % [con] Death penalty is a form of revenge.
arg(con42).  % [con] The death penalty is clearly more expensive than a system handling similar cases with a lesser punishment.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(pro60, pro74).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — B's claim that life is sacred directly contradicts A's conclusion that people will favor capital punishment.
att(con211, pro74).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B challenges the premise that people can weigh arguments properly by highlighting systemic injustice.
att(con72, pro74).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — B asserts that 'eye for an eye' is simplistic, directly opposing A's implication that empathy leads to support for capital punishment.
att(con208, pro74).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B characterizes the death penalty as revenge, undermining A's premise that empathy, not vengeance, drives support.
att(pro60, pro5).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — pro60’s claim that life is sacred directly opposes the implied conclusion that reinstating the death penalty is justified
att(con211, pro5).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — con211 argues the system is unjust, contradicting the implied pro‑death‑penalty conclusion of pro5
att(con72, pro5).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — con72 rejects the ‘eye for an eye’ justification, countering pro5’s implied endorsement of capital punishment
att(con208, pro5).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — con208 frames the death penalty as revenge, challenging the presumed conclusion that it is a legitimate policy
att(pro60, pro55).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B's premise that life is sacred challenges the underlying justification for capital punishment in A.
att(con211, pro55).  % [undermining] conf=80 — B claims the legal system fails to provide equal representation, challenging the premise that capital punishment can be fairly applied to premeditated murderers.
att(con72, pro55).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B calls the eye‑for‑an‑eye rationale simplistic, attacking the moral premise underlying A's claim that the death penalty is appropriate.
att(con208, pro55).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B labels the death penalty as revenge, undermining A's premise that it is a justified, non‑excessive response to premeditated murder.
att(pro60, pro55b).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — B's claim that life is sacred directly opposes A's justification of death penalty for murder.
att(con211, pro55b).  % [undermining] conf=90 — B argues the legal system fails to provide equal representation, undermining the premise that capital punishment can be fairly applied.
att(con72, pro55b).  % [undermining] conf=85 — B claims the 'eye for an eye' rationale is simplistic, attacking the moral premise behind A's support for death penalty.
att(con208, pro55b).  % [undermining] conf=80 — B labels the death penalty as revenge, challenging the justification A gives for its use.
att(pro60, pro62).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — B's claim that life is sacred directly opposes A's support for capital punishment.
att(con211, pro62).  % [undermining] conf=85 — B challenges the premise that the justice system can fairly punish violators by highlighting inadequate representation.
att(con72, pro62).  % [undermining] conf=80 — B questions the moral simplicity of 'eye for an eye', undermining A's fairness justification.
att(con208, pro62).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B labels the death penalty as revenge, attacking the premise that it is a fair form of justice.
att(pro60, pro62b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — 'Life is sacred' directly contradicts the claim that killers deserve death.
att(con211, pro62b).  % [undermining] conf=85 — The claim of inadequate representation challenges the premise that the death penalty is fairly applied.
att(con72, pro62b).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Labeling 'eye for an eye' as simplistic attacks the moral premise underlying the fairness claim.
